t of novel situations that you will encounter in running a public company, =
and you want to know=C2=A0what you are allowed to do in those situations. K=
nowing that in some situation the rules will be a bit more favorable =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0knowing that the rule is =E2=80=9Cwe can pay our CEO whatever we w=
ant=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is probably less important than knowing that=C2=
=A0in general=C2=A0the rules are predictable and reasonable, that you can r=
un your company=E2=80=99s affairs rationally rather than by guesswork.=C2=
=A0
On the other hand, if you are another US state (or a foreign jurisdiction),=
 and you want to induce companies to incorporate in your state rather than =
in Delaware, the=C2=A0main=C2=A0thing that you can offer is =E2=80=9Cwe wil=
l be even more management-friendly than Delaware.=E2=80=9D
  [2]
=C2=A0You can=E2=80=99t offer a deep body of precedent produced by expert j=
udges, or not yet anyway. But you can say =E2=80=9Chey, our rules aren=E2=
=80=99t really written yet, and you can=E2=80=99t entirely predict what the=
